n recupere la sortie sur une autre fichier \n  directe : on exe une cmd_sed sur un fichier puis le resultat s\'applique sur le fichier passee en entree',NULL,NULL,'2015-11-23 14:59:19'),(31,'#sed #intro #3','sed peut recevoir un script:\n  il y a 2facons de passer un scrip a sed:\n    sed -e __ici_le_script_uniligne__\n    sed -f __script_file__',NULL,NULL,'2015-11-23 14:59:25'),(32,'#sed #important #basis #4','2014-12-19 17:04:40','','\nsed -e __script_uniline__\n  ex: sed -e \'4d; 7d \' test.txt                 \n    -e : for the fact that the script \'4d; 7d \' will be performed in file_test.txt\n    -d : to delete\n      so \'4d; 7d \' meant to delete the line 4 AND 7    \n\n  ex : sed -e \'4,7 d\' test.txt\n  	to delete the line from 4 TILL 7\n\n','2015-11-23 14:59:31'),(33,'#sed #regex #intro',NULL,NULL,'\nsed \'/^# / d\' test.txt','2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(34,'#mysql #cluster #introduction #nodes','MySQL Clusters are built from three different types of node.\n  cluster = sum(3nodes)\n  3nodes:\n    management node\n    storage node\n    api node\n      used to extract data from db\n      most common is __mysqld__\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(35,'#mysql #cluster #install','\nu have to dl and install 2files\n  MySQL-Cluster-gpl-server-7.a.b-c.rhel5.x86_64.rpm\n  	this is about the server of the cluster\n  MySQL-client-community-5.a.b-c.rhel5.x86_64.rpm   	this is about the client of the cluster  \n\nafter installing these rpms, a file is created:\n  /etc/my.cnf\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(36,'#mysql #status check','\n$ service mysql status\nOR\n$ /etc/init.d mysql status\nOR\n$ telnet host00 3306\n  this is check if the server is up\n    and listening for connections on the port\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(37,'#mysql #log check','\nthe file of log is in:\n  /var/log/mysql/mysql.log\n    that is defined on the confFile in #general-log-file',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(38,'#sec #iptables #intro','\nhttp://lea-linux.org/documentations/Iptables\nu really need iptables to filter traffic which are permitted in ur serv\n  without ipt all traffics are almost allowed which is not good \n\n\navant de commencer iptables\n    il est bien de charger certains modules:\n        # modprobe ip_nat_ftp\n        # modprobe ip_nat_irc\n        # modprobe iptable_filter\n        # modprobe iptable_mangle\n        # modprobe iptable_nat  \nhttp://lea-linux.org/documentations/Iptables\n\nOn a high-level iptables might contain multiple tables. Tables might contain multiple chains. \n    Chains can be built-in or user-defined. Chains might contain multiple rules. Rules are defined for the packets.\n\nSo, the structure is: iptables -> Tables -> Chains -> Rules\nJust to re-iterate, tables are bunch of chains, and chains are bunch of firewall rules\n\nthis are 4basic tables\n    filter\n    nat\n    mangle\n    raw\n\n\nfor the filter_table, here are the chain for that table\n    INPUT\n        for the packets which come from the outside and go inside the server\n    OUTPUT\n        just understand the INPUT_chain, this is the opposite\n    FORWARD\n        a little bit difficult\n\nfor the nat_table, here are some_chains\n    PREROUTING\n        Alters packets _before_ routing\n        Packet translation happens immediately after the packet comes to the system\n    POSTROUTING\n        Alters packets _after_ routing\n        Packet translation happens when the packets are leaving the system\n    OUTPUT\n        see http://www.thegeekstuff.com/2011/01/iptables-fundamentals/\n\n\n\n\nsi on ne definit pas la table dans iptables alors\n    on est en train de modifier la table: FILTER\npour vider toutes les regles\n    iptables -F INPUT\n        on n_a pas mentionnee la table alors c_est la table par defaut: FILTER\n        on a flusher la table FILTER dont regle est INPUT\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-05-16 10:24:00'),(39,'#sec #iptables #intro #firewall #1','firewall do the analyse all packets.. do they respect the rules',NULL,'\nifk, to start with iptables, u must masterize the filter_table\n    if u don_t mention the name of a table then u will be set in the table_filter\n    \nto check the data which was like a stream in ur computer\n    iptables -L -v\n    it is not -V, it -v\n    the output will be\n        Chain INPUT (policy ACCEPT 9840 packets, 14M bytes)\n         pkts bytes target     prot opt in     out     source               destination         \n\n        Chain FORWARD (policy ACCEPT 0 packets, 0 bytes)\n         pkts bytes target     prot opt in     out     source               destination         \n\n        Chain OUTPUT (policy ACCEPT 7556 packets, 491K bytes)\n         pkts bytes target     prot opt in     out     source               destination \n    it tells about the packet which come in ur computer since it started\n        that output told me that since my pc started\n        I had 14MBytes which went in my computer\n            491kBytes which went out\n\nremember that many protocols use query/response way of communication\n    if u do a query, u will get a response\n        so there is INPUT and OUTPUT chains which are used\n\nto accept all stream from some chains                  -+\n    iptables --policy INPUT ACCEPT                      +--- that is to define the default action of \n    iptables --policy OUTPUT ACCEPT                     |         the chain\n    iptables --policy FORWARD ACCEPT                    |    ACCEPT: allow the connection\n                      +--+---+                          |    DROP: don_t consider the connection\n                         +------this are chains         |    REJECT: don_t accept the connection and\nif u want to drop the stream                            |       and send an error to the sender\n    iptables --policy INPUT DROP                       -+       ifk: this is most used in the chainINPUT\n\n\nto drop an INPUTconnection from some specific ip\n    iptables -A INPUT -s 10.10.10.10 -j DROP\n\nto flush everything\n    iptables -F\n','2015-11-23 15:02:21'),(40,'#sec #iptables #intro #firewall','criteria of filter are many: ports, protocols, addrIP, and more\n\niptables is very strict. then, if u want to activate iptables, u have to block everything, and right after, open what u want little by little',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(41,'#sec #log #auth #sys','to see who was logged into ur sys','/var/log/auth.log',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(42,'#sec #log #stuff #sys','stuff of log... errors, bugs, informations, .....','/var/log/message\n/var/log/syslog',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(43,'#sec #log #fail2ban','log of fail2ban... ','/var/log/fail2ban',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(44,'#sec #log #snort','log of snort... ','/var/log/snort/alert',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(45,'#sec #log #rkhunter','log of rkhunter... ','/var/log/rkhunter',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(46,'#sec #rkhunter #intro','if someone hacked ur sys, maybe he installed a backdoor in ur sys then he can rehack ur sys, and a rootkit to hide the hack\n\nrkhunter can detect rootkits on the server ',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(47,'#sec #conf #rkhunter','configuration_file of rkhunter','/etc/default/rkhunter',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(48,'#sec #intro','firewall had to block some connections, but the connections which are opened had to be controlled too,....\n  then we have ids (intrusion detection sys) and ips (intrustion prevention sys)\n    they are types of software which will detect all attempt of intrusion',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(49,'#sec #intro #1','those are the steps to do a classic intrusion:\n  scan port\n  simple attack\n  intrusion\n  how to log in the server on the purpose',NULL,NULL,'2015-11-23 15:02:50'),(50,'#sec #intro #portsentry','\nto block|manage who can scan ur port',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(51,'#sec #conf_file #portsentry #1','conf file of #portsentry','/usr/local/psionic/portsentry/portsentry.conf',NULL,'2015-11-23 15:03:35'),(52,'#sec #conf_file #portsentry','conf file of #portsentry','/etc/portsentry/portsentry.conf',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(53,'#sec #fail2ban #intro #definition','\nit is based on blocking ip which tried to log into some services and which it was failed\n  it will block the ip with iptables',NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 23:30:55'),(54,'#sec #fail2ban #conf',NULL,'/etc/fail2ban/jail.conf',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(55,'#sec #snort #intro','it is powerful and analyse the traffic in live, then ur sys can slow down with this\nhttp://www.trustonme.net/didactels/187.html\nhttp://doc.ubuntu-fr.org/snort\n    \n when bug appears, check /var/log/syslog\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(56,'#sec #log #logwatch #conf_file',NULL,'/usr/share/logwatch/default.conf/logwatch.conf',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(57,'#sys #conf_file #ssh',NULL,'/etc/ssh/sshd_config',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(58,'#sys #conf_file #apache2',NULL,'','\nhere is where u can conf ur apache2\n    /etc/apache2/apache2.conf\n\nerror log file\n    /var/log/apache2/error.log\n\naccess log file\n    /var/log/apache2/access.log\n\nto change the log file location\n    ErrorLog \"/home/httpd/cyberciti.biz/rawlogs/httpd-error.log\"\n    CustomLog \"/home/httpd/cyberciti.biz/rawlogs/httpd-access.log\" combined\n','2015-03-23 19:52:54'),(59,'#nmap','to scan port on a server and to make it verbose','nmap -v ip00','\nhttp://www.cyberciti.biz/networking/nmap-command-examples-tutorials/\nto scan a single host\n    nmap -v ip00\n    nmap -v server0.site00.com\n        # -v is for verbose\n\nto scan multiple addr\n    nmap -v 192.168.1.1,2,3,4   \n    nmap -v 192.168.1-20\n    nmap -v 192.168.1.*\n    nmap -v 192.168.1.0/24\n\nif the hosts u want is in /tmp/test_nmap,txt\n    nmap -iL /tmp/test_nmap.txt\n\nin a range of ip that u_re scanning, u want to exclude 2ip\n    nmap -V 192.168.1.0/24 --exclude ip00,ip01\n        ifk: don_t put space here---------^\n\n\nif the hosts that u don_t want to be scanned is in /tmp/exclude_nmap.txt\n    nmap -iL /tmp/test_nmap.txt --excludefile /tmp/exclude_nmap.txt\n\n\n\nto check os version of some host\n    nmap -v -A 192.168.1.1\n    if u want using file\n        nmap -vA -iL /tmp/test_nmap.txt\n\n\n\n\nto find out if some host00 is protected by a firewall\n    nmap -sA 192.168.1.254\n\nScan a host when protected by the firewall\n    nmap -PN 192.168.1.1\n\n\n\nScan a network and find out which servers and devices are up and running\n    nmap -sP 192.168.1.0/24\n\n\n\nto perform a fast scan\n    nmap -F 192.168.1.1\n\n\n\nOnly show open (or possibly open) ports\n    nmap --open 192.168.1.1\n\nto show all packets sent and received\nifk: packets used when doint the scan\n    nmap --packet-trace 192.168.1.1\n\n\nto show the routes\n    nmap --iflist\n\nto scan a specific port00 in host00\n    nmap -p 80 192.168.1.1\n    nmap -p 80,53 192.168.1.1   # 2ports\n    nmap -p 80-200 192.168.1.1  # range of ports\n    nmap -p T:80 192.168.1.1    # scan tcp_port\n    nmap -p U:80 192.168.1.1    # scan udp_port\n    nmap --top-ports 5 192.168.1.1\n        # to scan the 5top-ports\n    nmap -p \"*\" 192.168.1.1     # to scan all ports\n','2015-04-29 17:33:07'),(60,'#nessus #intro #sec','to scan vulnerabilities in ur sys',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(61,'#osi #memo #aide_memo','all people seems to need data processing\nOR\nplease, do not throw sausage pizza away',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(62,'#mysql #query #ifnull','this will select col00 and col01, but if col01 is null then it will be replaced by \'newVal\' in the select query only','select col00, IFNULL(col01,\'newVal\')',NULL,'2015-01-16 05:43:50'),(63,'#postfix #conf_file',NULL,'/etc/postfix/main.cf',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(64,'#postfix #package_to_install',NULL,'postfix postfix-mysql libasl2-2 libasl2-modules sasl2-bin libpam-mysql procmail',NULL,'2015-02-07 06:36:13'),(65,'#cisco #basis #intro #info #default','by default, all pc connected to sw are in vlan1. u can check it by: sw#show vlan',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-05 06:56:40'),(66