   ping -i 0.1\n\nto test if your loopback works\n    ping 0\n    ping localhost\n    ping 127.0.0.1\n\nto ping ip00 ad stop the ping after sending 5packets\n    ping -c 5 ip00\n\nto show the version of ping\n    ping -V\n\nto give beep when the host is reachable\n    ping -a ip00\n\nto change the size of the packet in ping, here we will change it to 100bytes\n    ping -s 100 ip00    \n        but the real packet which will be sent is 128bytes, bcz there will be 28bytes of header\n\nto get the summary of ping only\n    ping -c 5 -q ip00\n         |-+-|\n           +------to tell that I want to send only 5packets\n        the -q is used for telling that I want the summary\n\nto ping ip00 and ping will exit after 10sec of the target not reached \n    ping -w 1000 ip00\n\nto ping ip00 and to show the summary\n    after hitting <ctrl>|\n\nto ip00 but passing by ip01 ip02 ip03\n    ping ip01 ip02 ip03 ip00\n\nto ping ip00 and to show the ip where the packet was gone before reaching ip00\n    ping -R ip00\n    out:\n        ip10\n        ip11\n        ip00\n    this worked on blueline.mg\nto flood the target to packets sent by ping:\n    ping -f ip00\nto prevent from that \"ping flood\":\n    sysctl -w net.ipv4.icmp_echoreply_rate=10    \n\nto disable ping reply \n    echo \"1\" >  /proc/sys/net/ipv4/icmp_echo_ignore_all\nto enable ping reply again\n    echo \"0\" >  /proc/sys/net/ipv4/icmp_echo_ignore_all\n','2015-04-15 21:50:23'),(693,'#awk -default-file -used-in-some-lines-of-this-db','\n1)    Amit     Physics    80\n2)    Rahul    Maths      90\n3)    Shyam    Biology    87\n4)    Kedar    English    85\n5)    Hari     History    89\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-16 19:45:55'),(694,'#awk -prg_awk-saved_in-file -global-var',NULL,NULL,'\ncat marks.txt\n=========================================0\n1)    Amit     Physics    80\n2)    Rahul    Maths      90\n3)    Shyam    Biology    87\n4)    Kedar    English    85\n5)    Hari     History    89\n\nawk \'{print}\' marks.txt\n    wil